{"parse":{"title":"Michael Brough (game designer)","pageid":56267621,"revid":854949243,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux\" style=\"display:none\">New Zealand-born game designer</div>\n<p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n\n</p>\n<table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">Michael Brough</span></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Michael_Brough_(6120713406).jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Michael Brough (6120713406).jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Michael_Brough_%286120713406%29.jpg/220px-Michael_Brough_%286120713406%29.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"158\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Michael_Brough_%286120713406%29.jpg/330px-Michael_Brough_%286120713406%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Michael_Brough_%286120713406%29.jpg/440px-Michael_Brough_%286120713406%29.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2137\" data-file-height=\"1535\" /></a><div>Michael Brough at Berlin Indie Game Jam in 2011</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n<span style=\"display:none\"> (<span class=\"bday\">1985-05-20</span>) </span>20 May 1985<span class=\"noprint ForceAgeToShow\"> (age&#160;33)</span><br /><span class=\"birthplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Auckland,_New_Zealand\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Auckland, New Zealand\">Auckland, New Zealand</a></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Occupation</th><td class=\"role\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Game_designer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Game designer\">Game designer</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Website</th><td>\n<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.smestorp.com/\">http://www.smestorp.com/</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Michael Brough</b> (born 20 May 1985) is a <a href=\"/wiki/New_Zealand\" title=\"New Zealand\">New Zealand</a>-born<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Indie_video_game\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Indie video game\">indie video game</a> developer known for his eclectic <a href=\"/wiki/Roguelike\" title=\"Roguelike\">roguelike</a> games. His games are often tightly-focused explorations of a single mechanical aspect of the roguelike genre, set on unusually small grids.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Couture_2018_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Couture_2018-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> This style of game, perhaps best exemplified by <a href=\"/wiki/868-HACK\" title=\"868-HACK\">868-HACK</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Nowak_2013_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nowak_2013-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>, has become widely known as the \"Broughlike\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Warp_Door_2015_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Warp_Door_2015-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Wired_Magazine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wired Magazine\">Wired Magazine</a> called Brough's games \"corrupted\" and \"brilliant\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-Rigney_2013_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Rigney_2013-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> while <a href=\"/wiki/The_Guardian\" title=\"The Guardian\">The Guardian</a> wrote that his work is \"strange\" and \"elegant\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Stuart_2013_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Stuart_2013-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Design_philosophy\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Design philosophy</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Award_nominations\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Award nominations</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Selected_works\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Selected works</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Design_philosophy\">Design philosophy</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Michael_Brough_(game_designer)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Design philosophy\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Brough believes that games are best understood within genres, which led him to focus on the roguelike game genre. He cites early roguelike <a href=\"/wiki/Castle_of_the_Winds\" title=\"Castle of the Winds\">Castle of the Winds</a> as an early inspiration.<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> One design problem with the original <a href=\"/wiki/Rogue_(video_game)\" title=\"Rogue (video game)\">Rogue</a> and subsequent roguelikes, Brough argues, is a large game board (80x20 tiles in Rogue) which leads to the player running down long corridors and \"not making choices.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> In comparison, classic board games like <a href=\"/wiki/Chess\" title=\"Chess\">Chess</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Go_(game)\" title=\"Go (game)\">Go</a> use 8x8 and 19x19 board sizes. \"You should never need a larger possibility space than Go,\" says Brough.<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> For one of his first roguelike games, <i>Zaga-33</i>, Brough specifically limited the board size to 9x9.<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/868-HACK\" title=\"868-HACK\">868-HACK</a>, <i>Imbroglio,</i> and <i>Cinco Paus</i> took this trend even further, with 6x6, 4x4, and 5x5 boards respectively.\n</p><p>Brough also identifies another design problem in roguelikes which he likens to <a href=\"/wiki/Zugzwang\" title=\"Zugzwang\">Zugzwang</a> in Chess, when the game forces you to move into a bad situation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Most roguelikes implement a \"Wait\" command to let the player pass their turn, forcing monsters to move into a bad position instead; however, Brough argues this is a poor solution and thus he tries to avoid implementing wait actions in his games.<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> \"Attacking is already a form of waiting\" since combatants stay in the same positions before and after the attack, which means enemies are already \"resources for waiting.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> To try to innovate on this Zugzwang problem, <i>868-HACK</i> lets the player use ranged attacks, as well as consume resources to use a \".WAIT\" ability if they have acquired it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-PRACTICE_2013_7-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PRACTICE_2013-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Award_nominations\">Award nominations</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Michael_Brough_(game_designer)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Award nominations\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>His games <i>Vesper.5</i>, <i>Corrypt</i>, and <i>BECOME A GREAT ARTIST IN JUST 10 SECONDS</i> were finalists for the IGF's <a href=\"/wiki/Independent_Games_Festival#Nuovo_(Innovation)_Award_($5,000)\" title=\"Independent Games Festival\">Nuovo Award</a> in 2013,<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> 2014,<sup id=\"cite_ref-:02_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:02-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> and 2015<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> respectively, and <a href=\"/wiki/868-HACK\" title=\"868-HACK\">868-HACK</a> and <i>Imbroglio</i> were finalists for the <a href=\"/wiki/Independent_Games_Festival#Excellence_in_Design_($3,000)\" title=\"Independent Games Festival\">Excellence in Design</a> award in 2014<sup id=\"cite_ref-:02_9-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:02-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> and 2017.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Selected_works\">Selected works</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Michael_Brough_(game_designer)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Selected works\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cinco_Paus&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Cinco Paus (page does not exist)\">Cinco Paus</a></i> (2017)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Imbroglio_(video_game)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Imbroglio (video game) (page does not exist)\">Imbroglio</a></i> (2016)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Helix_(2014_video_game)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Helix (2014 video game) (page does not exist)\">Helix</a></i> (2014)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/868-HACK\" title=\"868-HACK\">868-HACK</a></i> (2013)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Become_a_Great_Artist_in_Just_10_Seconds&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Become a Great Artist in Just 10 Seconds (page does not exist)\">Become a Great Artist in Just 10 Seconds</a></i> (2013)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Corrpyt&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Corrpyt (page does not exist)\">Corrpyt</a></i> (2012)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Vesper.5&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Vesper.5 (page does not exist)\">Vesper.5</a></i> (2012)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Zaga-33&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Zaga-33 (page does not exist)\">Zaga-33</a></i> (2012)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Glitch_Tank&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Glitch Tank (page does not exist)\">Glitch Tank</a></i> (2011)</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Michael_Brough_(game_designer)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://nzgda.com/about-us/nz-gamedev/\">\"NZ Game Development Industry\"</a>. <i>New Zealand Game Developers Association</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=New+Zealand+Game+Developers+Association&amp;rft.atitle=NZ+Game+Development+Industry&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fnzgda.com%2Fabout-us%2Fnz-gamedev%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMichael+Brough+%28game+designer%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Couture_2018-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Couture_2018_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Couture, Joel (15 January 2018). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/273314/Freedom_through_constraints_The_design_of_Michael_Broughs_Imbroglio.php\">\"Freedom through constraints: The design of Michael Brough's Imbroglio\"</a>. <i>Gamasutra</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">16 January</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Gamasutra&amp;rft.atitle=Freedom+through+constraints%3A+The+design+of+Michael+Brough%27s+Imbroglio&amp;rft.date=2018-01-15&amp;rft.aulast=Couture&amp;rft.aufirst=Joel&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.gamasutra.com%2Fview%2Fnews%2F273314%2FFreedom_through_constraints_The_design_of_Michael_Broughs_Imbroglio.php&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMichael+Brough+%28game+designer%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Nowak_2013-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Nowak_2013_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Nowak, Mike (30 August 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.pockettactics.com/reviews/review-hack-868/\">\"Review: 868-HACK\"</a>. <i>Pocket Tactics</i><span class